WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:25.719
Hi everyone, I am Samuel, I work at the Life Sciences team at Posit as a Solution Architect.

00:00:25.719 --> 00:00:33.880
Today we are going to discuss a real-world evidence generation workflow within Posit's team ecosystem.

00:00:33.880 --> 00:00:51.380
We'll showcase how epidemiologists, data scientists, and RWD programmers can work collaboratively within the Posit team platform to generate high-quality evidence that can be shared with internal and external stakeholders.

00:00:51.380 --> 00:01:00.340
Two quick definitions before we get started. RWD or Real-World Data is patient data collected outside a clinical trial.

00:01:00.340 --> 00:01:08.040
This includes electronic health records, insurance claims, patient registries, and variables.

00:01:08.040 --> 00:01:20.540
Real-World Evidence or RWE is what we get when we apply rigorous methods to real-world data for answering clinical or economic questions.

00:01:20.540 --> 00:01:26.940
We can think of RWD as the raw material and RWE as the finished insight.

00:01:26.940 --> 00:01:46.339
Today we'll showcase how Posit can take us from fragmented analysis to a reproducible submission-aligned evidence package in one governed workflow.

00:01:46.339 --> 00:01:54.099
Real-World Evidence is reshaping how drugs are approved, priced, and used globally.

00:01:54.099 --> 00:02:04.540
A few forces are making this urgent. Regulators now actively accept RWE for level expansions and HTA decisions.

00:02:04.540 --> 00:02:20.440
Clinical trials cannot answer every question. Rare diseases, long-term safety, and pediatric dosing all require observational evidence, and payers own grand formulary access without it.

00:02:20.440 --> 00:02:25.240
RWE is no longer optional.

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:37.940
Traditional use cases of real-world data includes Health Economic Outcomes Research or HEOR, market access, post-marketing commitments, safety monitoring.

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:41.300
These are all well-established use cases.

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:57.860
Teams are increasingly using RWD for clinical trial optimization, trial feasibility, external control arms, adverse event prediction, and inclusive recruitments.

00:02:57.860 --> 00:03:06.899
All of this requires the same thing, reproducible and auditable analysis.

00:03:06.899 --> 00:03:20.059
Most teams who are dealing with real-world data are stuck with fragmented data access, manual ad hoc scripts, results pasted into PowerPoint, and no audit trail.

00:03:20.059 --> 00:03:32.600
Every data refresh means rebuilding from scratch. Regulators and reviewers cannot trace findings to source. These are reproducibility failures.

00:03:32.600 --> 00:03:40.559
Posit removes these frictions as an integrated data science platform built around three key components.

00:03:40.559 --> 00:03:53.059
Workbench, which is a governed compute environment for R and Python, Package Manager that locks package versions for long-term reproducibility, and Posit Connect,

00:03:53.059 --> 00:04:02.440
where users can publish Quarto documents, Shiny apps, and dashboards with audit trails and role-based access.

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:15.179
Posit team can be deployed in all major cloud provider. It can also be deployed on-prem within an air-gapped environment.

00:04:15.179 --> 00:04:19.779
It can also be deployed as Snowflake native application.

00:04:19.779 --> 00:04:28.500
In our demo, the environment that we use is deployed within Snowflake as a Snowflake native app.

00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:37.299
And the real-world data that we are using also sits within a Snowflake database.

00:04:37.299 --> 00:04:43.500
So you may ask, why would you build your real-world workflow within Posit?

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:49.339
The primary reasons are you can own your real-world evidence end-to-end.

00:04:49.339 --> 00:04:59.779
You prototype, validate, and deploy in one environment where governance is already built in.

00:04:59.779 --> 00:05:05.739
This is what will lead you to a faster innovation.

00:05:05.739 --> 00:05:18.679
In our demo, we focused on a hypothetical study built on synthetic data set where we are looking at post-approval comparative effectiveness in type 2 diabetes.

00:05:18.679 --> 00:05:30.480
We want to identify new users of ASU and compare them with DPP4 inhibitors users within a synthetic Medicare claims population.

00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:35.779
And the data is already mapped to OMOP common data model.

00:05:35.779 --> 00:05:41.920
We'll use control for measured confounding using propensity score matching techniques.

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:49.660
We'd like to estimate time-to-first inpatient cardiovascular hospitalization using survival analysis.

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:59.079
We also want to quantify the hazard ratio within 95% confidence interval via Cox proportional hazards model.

00:05:59.079 --> 00:06:15.480
At the end, we want to publish a pair evidence package to Posit Connect where internal and external stakeholders can access both the results and the underlying codes.

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:20.619
Snowflake holds the data behind secure role-based access.

00:06:20.619 --> 00:06:34.119
Workbench runs the analysis and evidence is served through Posit Connect in forms of dashboard, HTML or Quarto documents, and web apps.

00:06:34.119 --> 00:06:43.380
Package managers ensures governed and curated R and Python packages are served to Workbench and Connect.

00:06:43.380 --> 00:06:58.239
Business users like an epidemiologist will usually interact with dashboards and web apps that are hosted in Connect and published by data scientists and RWD programmer.

00:06:58.239 --> 00:07:03.739
Let's go into the live demo to get a better understanding of this type of interaction.

00:07:13.380 --> 00:07:24.920
I just launched my Posit team from Snowpark container services.

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:33.980
Here you can see the three components of Posit team, Posit Workbench, Posit Connect and Posit Package Manager.

00:07:33.980 --> 00:07:50.820
Now let's see how an epidemiologist or a business stakeholder would interact with an existing application that has been published by their data science team.

00:07:50.820 --> 00:08:00.420
This application is built by the data scientist and exposed to business users through Posit Connect.

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:05.579
The Shiny app is built using QueryChat.

00:08:05.579 --> 00:08:21.380
QueryChat brings in chatbot component within Shiny applications that allows end users to ask natural language questions to underlying data.

00:08:21.380 --> 00:08:31.540
QueryChat can connect to remote data sources, including Snowflake, Databricks, Redshift and Oracle.

00:08:31.540 --> 00:08:37.479
As an epidemiologist, I can come here and I start asking different questions about my data.

00:08:37.479 --> 00:08:43.340
For example, how many patients have type 2 diabetes?

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:52.340
So what's happening now, QueryChat is leveraging LLM to generate the SQL query.

00:08:52.340 --> 00:08:59.599
Then QueryChat is executing the query against the connected data source.

00:08:59.599 --> 00:09:04.479
It's important to understand the separation here.

00:09:04.479 --> 00:09:10.880
Data is not exposed to LLM directly, only the data schema is.

00:09:10.940 --> 00:09:22.820
And once the LLM returns the SQL query, the application itself executes that SQL against the data source.

00:09:22.820 --> 00:09:31.979
So here you can see it identified 8,150 patients have type 2 diabetes in the data sets.

00:09:31.979 --> 00:09:38.419
Now I may want to also do more complex jobs, right?

00:09:38.419 --> 00:09:44.919
For example, how many patients with type 2 diabetes are also taking metformin?

00:09:44.919 --> 00:09:57.919
This query will require joining of two different data tables, one for the patient condition, another for the patient drugs.

00:09:57.919 --> 00:10:07.960
And you can see it identifies properly the patients with type 2 diabetes that are also taking metformin.

00:10:07.960 --> 00:10:21.719
So this application becomes the primary entry point for an epidemiologist when they are designing the observational study for real-world evidence generation.

00:10:21.719 --> 00:10:34.419
Before a data scientist or RWD programmer start coding, epidemiologists can first have a good idea of the underlying data source with the help from an LLM.

00:10:34.419 --> 00:10:41.159
At the same time, we can ask API Assistant to update the dashboard.

00:10:41.159 --> 00:10:58.479
For example, if I tell it, show me type 2 diabetes patients who are not on metformin.

00:10:58.479 --> 00:11:10.280
You can see it's updating the dashboard and showing 1,455 patients with type 2 diabetes who are not on metformin.

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:31.219
In the same dashboard, we have Condition Explorer, where we can see top 15 conditions by patient count, top 15 conditions by error count, and then conditions summary.

00:11:31.219 --> 00:11:37.080
There is another tool within this web app, which is called Cohort Builder.

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:53.580
This is where an epidemiologist can come in and apply different exclusion and inclusion criteria to ensure they are getting enough patients to conduct the observational study.

00:11:53.580 --> 00:12:03.619
So they can come here and without writing a single SQL query, they can start playing around.

00:12:03.619 --> 00:12:20.020
So if I, as an epidemiologist, looking for patients cohort with type 2 diabetes, but at the same time, I want this patient to have a prior condition, such as hypertension,

00:12:20.020 --> 00:12:30.159
I can click on this build cohort, and what it will do is query the Snowflake database and bring back the summary results on the front end.

00:12:30.159 --> 00:12:39.460
So I can see here, if I apply all these conditions, eventually I'll have a patient cohort of size about 3,000.

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:53.760
So all these interactive tools, including the chatbot, which is built with QueryChat, allows the EPI to design the observational study.

00:12:53.760 --> 00:13:09.299
Once they are satisfied with all the exclusion and inclusion criteria and the data quality, they can provide a green signal to the data scientist to carry on the rest of the analysis.

00:13:09.299 --> 00:13:18.500
So that analysis will take place within Posit Workbench.

00:13:18.500 --> 00:13:25.159
Posit Workbench is where the data scientists usually live.

00:13:25.159 --> 00:13:30.260
You can see we have multiple projects here.

00:13:30.260 --> 00:13:34.500
And I can create a new session.

00:13:34.500 --> 00:13:39.940
And here I have my credentials to Snowflake attached to my session.

00:13:39.940 --> 00:13:47.840
So I'll launch this session.

00:13:47.900 --> 00:13:53.280
And here I have a Quarto document open.

00:13:53.280 --> 00:14:04.940
So this Quarto document was built with the help of Positron Assistant, and we'll just look at the final results.

00:14:04.940 --> 00:14:15.880
But Positron Assistant has the full context of the data source that sits within Snowflake.

00:14:15.919 --> 00:14:25.320
So here you can see OMOP Common Data Model data source from where we are pulling all the data for our analysis.

00:14:25.320 --> 00:14:32.679
And to get to this data, I don't need to remember any token, username, or password.

00:14:32.679 --> 00:14:39.080
Everything is already managed through Workbench.

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:45.820
So I can click on Preview, which will render this Quarto document.

00:14:45.820 --> 00:14:52.619
And this Quarto document will act as our integrated evidence package.

00:14:52.619 --> 00:14:59.559
So from the guidance of epidemiologists, we build our cohort.

00:14:59.559 --> 00:15:03.719
We run all the different statistical analysis.

00:15:03.719 --> 00:15:10.419
And then we get a publishable document.

00:15:10.419 --> 00:15:16.919
Once this run is complete, you can see the document on the right-hand side.

00:15:16.919 --> 00:15:25.219
Here you can see we have a diagram of the overall workflow, how the analysis was done.

00:15:25.219 --> 00:15:29.359
We have a study overview.

00:15:29.359 --> 00:15:34.119
Then we describe how the data was connected.

00:15:34.119 --> 00:15:43.179
If I click on Show Code, I can see the underlying code that pulled the data.

00:15:43.179 --> 00:15:51.460
We can look at the different concept definition, like what is the concept for type 2 diabetes?

00:15:51.460 --> 00:15:56.859
What is the concept for a specific drug that we are interested in?

00:15:56.859 --> 00:16:04.619
This is the outcome, which is inpatient visit, hypertension, heart failure, and chronic kidney disease.

00:16:04.619 --> 00:16:10.260
So all these codes that are required to build a cohort.

00:16:10.260 --> 00:16:16.020
And these concepts are part of OMOP Common Data Model.

00:16:16.020 --> 00:16:19.859
Now we can look at eligibility criteria.

00:16:19.859 --> 00:16:30.919
And this is where epidemiologists can confirm that the programmers followed the design they have created.

00:16:30.919 --> 00:16:41.619
And again, you can see we'll have code here, which we can hide or expand as needed.

00:16:41.619 --> 00:16:48.299
So this provides a nice summary of code and result living together.

00:16:48.299 --> 00:16:54.260
We have the baseline characteristics with propensity score matching,

00:16:54.260 --> 00:17:01.299
how the standard difference between different confounding factors were before the propensity score matching,

00:17:01.299 --> 00:17:07.660
and how it looks after propensity score matching, and can compare and see.

00:17:07.660 --> 00:17:14.640
Here you can see the survival analysis with the Kaplan-Meier curves and Cox proportional hazard model.

00:17:14.640 --> 00:17:20.300
We are not going to dive deep into the results because this is a synthetic data.

00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:28.199
What I want to highlight is the way this document is generated and what message it conveys.

00:17:28.199 --> 00:17:40.540
We can attach all our methodological notes and also determine where the outputs are saved.

00:17:40.540 --> 00:17:47.599
So once the data scientist or the RWE programmer is satisfied with this document,

00:17:47.599 --> 00:17:52.699
they can decide to publish it to Connect.

00:17:52.699 --> 00:17:59.500
Positron IDE provides this one-button publishing option,

00:17:59.500 --> 00:18:07.140
where you can come here and just select the documents you want to publish and deploy your project.

00:18:07.140 --> 00:18:16.599
You can see your publishing logs here, and once it's published, it will be accessible through Project Connect.

00:18:16.599 --> 00:18:32.199
So now this document can be shared within my organization and also to external stakeholders.

00:18:32.199 --> 00:18:40.500
So what we have covered in this demo is first, as an epidemiologist, you can interact through a web app

00:18:40.500 --> 00:18:48.900
with interactive chatbot and other tools to design your observational study.

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:59.160
Once the design phase is complete, a data scientist or an RWD programmer can work within the workbench to generate a Quarto document

00:18:59.160 --> 00:19:11.359
that is also again published in Project Connect with necessary results, figures, and code.

